INSERT INTO Guide (titre, description, contenu, categorie) VALUES

-- 1. Architecture
('Target Active Directory Architecture',
 'Reference description of the GOAD-Light AD environment: forest and domains, hosts, notable accounts, groups and exposed services.',
 '# Target Active Directory Architecture\n\nThis guide describes the Active Directory environment that is deployed as the\nattack target of the platform. It is intended as a reference document — the\nkind of architecture briefing a consultant typically receives at the\nbeginning of a real engagement.\n\n## Forest and Domain Layout\n\nThe lab is built on the **GOAD-Light** topology. It consists of a single\nforest containing two domains in a parent-child relationship.\n\n| Element       | Value                          |\n|---------------|--------------------------------|\n| Forest root   | `sevenkingdoms.local`          |\n| Child domain  | `north.sevenkingdoms.local`    |\n| Trust         | Bidirectional parent-child     |\n\nThe trust between the two domains is established by default at domain creation\nand allows authenticated principals from one domain to access resources in the\nother, subject to access controls.\n\n## Domain Controllers and Servers\n\nThree Windows Server 2019 machines compose the lab:\n\n| Hostname       | FQDN                                       | Role                  | IP             |\n|----------------|--------------------------------------------|-----------------------|----------------|\n| `kingslanding` | `kingslanding.sevenkingdoms.local`         | Domain controller     | `10.2.10.10`   |\n| `winterfell`   | `winterfell.north.sevenkingdoms.local`     | Domain controller     | `10.2.10.11`   |\n| `castelblack`  | `castelblack.north.sevenkingdoms.local`    | Member server         | `10.2.10.22`   |\n\n`kingslanding` is the domain controller of the root domain `sevenkingdoms.local`.\n`winterfell` is the domain controller of the child domain `north.sevenkingdoms.local`.\n`castelblack` is a regular member server joined to the child domain; it hosts\napplication-level services (IIS, MSSQL) and is a frequent target for lateral\nmovement and privilege escalation scenarios.\n\n## Notable User Accounts\n\nThe following table lists the accounts that are most relevant for offensive\nand defensive scenarios. The lab contains additional accounts, but those\nlisted below are the ones typically exercised by attack chains and worth\nremembering.\n\n| Account                                | Domain                       | Notes                                                |\n|----------------------------------------|------------------------------|------------------------------------------------------|\n| `sevenkingdoms\\robert.baratheon`       | `sevenkingdoms.local`        | Domain Admin of the root domain                      |\n| `sevenkingdoms\\cersei.lannister`       | `sevenkingdoms.local`        | Domain Admin of the root domain                      |\n| `north\\eddard.stark`                   | `north.sevenkingdoms.local`  | Domain Admin; simulated activity (LLMNR queries)     |\n| `north\\catelyn.stark`                  | `north.sevenkingdoms.local`  | Local admin on `winterfell`                          |\n| `north\\robb.stark`                     | `north.sevenkingdoms.local`  | Local admin on `winterfell`; simulated LLMNR traffic |\n| `north\\jon.snow`                       | `north.sevenkingdoms.local`  | Holds an MSSQL trusted link to `castelblack`         |\n| `north\\jeor.mormont`                   | `north.sevenkingdoms.local`  | Local admin on `castelblack`                         |\n\n## Notable Groups\n\n| Group           | Domain                  | Privilege                         |\n|-----------------|-------------------------|-----------------------------------|\n| `Small Council` | `sevenkingdoms.local`   | Members can RDP into `kingslanding` |\n| `Baratheon`     | `sevenkingdoms.local`   | Members can RDP into `kingslanding` |\n| `Starks`        | `north.sevenkingdoms.local` | Members can RDP into `winterfell` and `castelblack` |\n| `Night''s Watch` | `north.sevenkingdoms.local` | Members can RDP into `castelblack` |\n\n## Exposed Services\n\n- **kingslanding** — Active Directory Certificate Services (AD CS) is installed\n  with a vulnerable certificate template (see *Vulnerabilities Inventory*).\n- **winterfell** — Standard domain controller services. NTLM downgrade is\n  enabled, and unauthenticated RPC user enumeration is allowed.\n- **castelblack** — IIS web server with unrestricted ASP file upload,\n  Microsoft SQL Server with a trusted link to another instance, and Windows\n  Defender disabled.\n\n## Summary\n\nThe architecture deliberately reproduces the kind of multi-domain, slightly\nneglected enterprise environment commonly encountered during real assessments.\nIt exposes weaknesses at every layer — credentials, Kerberos, ACLs,\ncertificate services, application services — making it a suitable target for\nend-to-end attack chains and detection engineering exercises.',
 'architecture'),

-- 2. Vulnerabilities Inventory
('Lab Vulnerabilities Inventory',
 'Catalog of the misconfigurations and intentional weaknesses present in the lab, grouped by family and detailed by technique.',
 '# Lab Vulnerabilities Inventory\n\nThis document lists the misconfigurations and intentional weaknesses present\nin the lab. They are grouped into families to help learners reason about\nthe underlying classes of attack rather than memorizing isolated tricks.\nEach family also lists the specific techniques exploitable in this\nenvironment.\n\n## 1. Credential-Based Weaknesses\n\nThese weaknesses allow an attacker to obtain, guess, or recover user\ncredentials with relatively low effort.\n\n- **Weak passwords** — Several accounts use predictable or short passwords\n  that fall to dictionary or password-spraying attacks.\n- **Password reuse across accounts** — A password obtained on one account\n  often grants access elsewhere.\n- **Cleartext credentials in shares and scripts** — Passwords are sometimes\n  left in scripts, GPO preferences, or shared documents accessible to\n  authenticated users.\n\n## 2. Kerberos-Related Attacks\n\nThe Kerberos authentication protocol is the backbone of Active Directory\nauthentication. The lab exposes the classical abuses that arise when its\nconfiguration is not hardened.\n\n- **Kerberoasting** — Service accounts have a Service Principal Name (SPN)\n  registered, allowing any authenticated user to request a service ticket\n  whose encrypted portion can be cracked offline.\n- **AS-REP Roasting** — Some accounts have Kerberos pre-authentication\n  disabled, allowing an attacker to request an authentication response\n  without knowing the password and crack it offline.\n- **Unconstrained / Constrained delegation abuse** — Certain machines or\n  accounts are configured with delegation rights that can be abused to\n  impersonate privileged users.\n\n## 3. ACL and Privilege Escalation\n\nActive Directory access control lists govern who can do what to whom.\nThe lab includes several intentionally permissive ACLs.\n\n- **Excessive `GenericAll` / `WriteDACL` rights** — Some users hold\n  extensive rights over privileged objects, allowing them to reset\n  passwords, modify group membership, or take ownership.\n- **DCSync rights granted to non-administrators** — A user without Domain\n  Admin privileges holds the rights required to perform a DCSync attack\n  and replicate password hashes from the domain controller.\n- **Local administrator rights on member servers** — Several domain\n  users are configured as local administrators on `winterfell` and\n  `castelblack`, opening the way for credential harvesting and lateral\n  movement.\n\n## 4. NTLM Relay and Coercion\n\nThese attacks exploit the way Windows machines authenticate to one\nanother over the network.\n\n- **LLMNR / NBT-NS poisoning** — Two simulated users (`eddard.stark` and\n  `robb.stark`) periodically issue LLMNR queries that an attacker on the\n  same broadcast segment can poison to capture NTLM hashes.\n- **NTLM relay on `winterfell`** — SMB signing is not enforced on the\n  child domain controller, making it a viable relay target.\n- **NTLM downgrade on `winterfell`** — The domain controller accepts\n  weakened NTLM authentication that is more amenable to offline\n  cracking.\n- **Unauthenticated RPC user enumeration** on `winterfell` — An\n  unauthenticated attacker can enumerate domain users through anonymous\n  RPC calls.\n\n## 5. Active Directory Certificate Services (ADCS) Abuse\n\n`kingslanding` hosts a Certification Authority configured with a\nvulnerable certificate template.\n\n- **ESC1** — A certificate template allows enrollees to specify an\n  arbitrary `subjectAltName`, making it possible to request a\n  certificate that authenticates as another user, including a Domain\n  Admin.\n\n## 6. Application-Level Vulnerabilities on `castelblack`\n\n`castelblack` exposes additional application-layer weaknesses on top of\nthe AD-level ones.\n\n- **IIS with unrestricted ASP file upload** — A misconfigured upload\n  feature allows an attacker to drop and execute server-side scripts.\n- **MSSQL `xp_cmdshell` and `EXECUTE AS`** — The SQL Server instance\n  allows command execution as a privileged user through SQL features\n  that are enabled and accessible.\n- **MSSQL trusted link** — A trusted database link from another instance\n  permits cross-server command execution under the privileges of the\n  linking account (`jon.snow`).\n- **Windows Defender disabled** — `castelblack` is the only host on\n  which the antivirus is intentionally turned off, making the execution\n  of common offensive tooling significantly easier.\n\n## How to Use This Inventory\n\nThis list is provided for learning and lab-based experimentation only.\nA typical purple-team exercise on this environment will pick one\nweakness from this catalog, run the corresponding attack in Caldera,\ninspect the resulting alerts in Wazuh, and use the gap analysis to tune\nthe detection rules.',
 'architecture'),

-- 3. Network Topology
('Lab Network Topology',
 'Description of the lab network: VLAN segmentation, hosts per zone, router interfaces and inter-VLAN traffic flows.',
 '# Lab Network Topology\n\nThis guide describes how the lab network is segmented, how the different\ncomponents are reachable, and which paths data follows during a simulation.\n\n## VLAN Segmentation\n\nThe lab is segmented into four VLANs, each dedicated to a single function.\n\n| VLAN | Name        | Purpose                                | Subnet         |\n|------|-------------|----------------------------------------|----------------|\n| 10   | Targets     | Active Directory target environment    | `10.2.10.0/24` |\n| 20   | SOC         | Defensive monitoring (Wazuh SIEM)      | `10.2.20.0/24` |\n| 30   | Attacker    | Offensive infrastructure (Caldera)     | `10.2.30.0/24` |\n| 40   | Management  | Web application and platform pilot     | `10.2.40.0/24` |\n\nThe four VLANs are interconnected through a Debian-based router that has\none interface per VLAN plus an external interface for Internet access.\n\n## Hosts by VLAN\n\n### VLAN 10 — Targets\n\n| Host           | IP            | Role                             |\n|----------------|---------------|----------------------------------|\n| `kingslanding` | `10.2.10.10`  | Domain controller (root domain)  |\n| `winterfell`   | `10.2.10.11`  | Domain controller (child domain) |\n| `castelblack`  | `10.2.10.22`  | Member server                    |\n\n### VLAN 20 — SOC\n\n| Host            | IP            | Role                            |\n|-----------------|---------------|---------------------------------|\n| `wazuh-server`  | `10.2.20.80`  | Wazuh SIEM (manager + indexer)  |\n\n### VLAN 30 — Attacker\n\n| Host             | IP            | Role                                 |\n|------------------|---------------|--------------------------------------|\n| `caldera-server` | `10.2.30.49`  | Caldera command-and-control server   |\n\n### VLAN 40 — Management\n\n| Host                | IP            | Role                                 |\n|---------------------|---------------|--------------------------------------|\n| `appli-web-server`  | `10.2.40.90`  | Web application (Next.js + MySQL)    |\n\n### Router\n\n| Interface | VLAN         | IP                  |\n|-----------|--------------|---------------------|\n| `ens18`   | WAN          | `192.0.2.102/24`    |\n| `ens19`   | VLAN 10      | `10.2.10.254/24`    |\n| `ens20`   | VLAN 20      | `10.2.20.254/24`    |\n| `ens21`   | VLAN 30      | `10.2.30.254/24`    |\n| `ens22`   | VLAN 40      | `10.2.40.254/24`    |\n\nEach VLAN''s gateway is the `.254` address of its subnet.\n\n## Communication Flows\n\nThree categories of traffic flow across these VLANs during a simulation\ncycle:\n\n- **Attack flow (VLAN 30 → VLAN 10).** The Caldera server delivers\n  instructions to the Caldera agents pre-installed on the target hosts.\n  The agents execute the techniques locally and report back to the\n  Caldera server.\n- **Logging flow (VLAN 10 → VLAN 20).** Wazuh agents installed on the\n  target hosts continuously forward Windows event logs and Sysmon\n  events to the Wazuh manager, where rules are applied and alerts are\n  generated.\n- **Orchestration flow (VLAN 40 → VLANs 20 and 30).** The web\n  application calls the REST APIs of the Wazuh manager and the Caldera\n  server to trigger attacks, retrieve alerts, and adjust detection\n  rules. The application itself never communicates directly with the\n  target hosts.\n\n## Why This Segmentation Matters\n\nThe four-zone layout intentionally mirrors the separation of concerns\nfound in a real enterprise environment: offensive activity, defensive\nmonitoring, and platform management are kept in distinct network\nsegments. This reflects the realistic posture under which a SOC operates\nand prevents accidental contamination between the lab''s zones.',
 'architecture'),

-- 4. Reading Wazuh logs (blue team)
('Reading Logs in Wazuh',
 'Practical guide to navigating the Wazuh dashboard, reading alert structure and running a basic investigation workflow.',
 '# Reading Logs in Wazuh\n\nThis guide is a practical entry point to the Wazuh interface for analysts\nwho need to investigate alerts produced during a simulation. It assumes\nthe default Wazuh dashboard, with no custom dashboards or rule packs\nbeyond what ships with the platform.\n\n## Accessing the Wazuh Interface\n\nThe Wazuh dashboard is available at `https://10.2.20.80` (HTTPS, default\nport). Authenticate with the credentials provided by the lab\nadministrator.\n\nAfter login, the landing page is the **Wazuh Overview**, which summarizes\nthe agents currently reporting and the latest security events. From here,\ntwo modules are most relevant for daily analysis:\n\n- **Modules → Security Events** — the central place for inspecting alerts.\n- **Agents** — the list of monitored hosts (here: the three target\n  Windows machines).\n\n## The Security Events Module\n\nThis module is where most investigation work happens. Three areas matter:\n\n1. **Alert timeline.** A histogram of alerts over time. Use it to spot\n   spikes during or after a simulation run.\n2. **Alert table.** The detailed list, sortable and filterable. Each\n   alert exposes its rule ID, rule level, agent, and the matched log\n   entry.\n3. **Filter bar.** Lets you narrow alerts by agent name, rule level, or\n   any field present in the alert document. The filter syntax follows\n   the Wazuh Query Language (WQL).\n\n## Anatomy of a Wazuh Alert\n\nA Wazuh alert is structured around three layers of information:\n\n- **Rule metadata** — `rule.id`, `rule.level`, `rule.description`. The\n  level ranges from 0 (informational) to 15 (critical). Anything from\n  level 7 upward is generally worth investigating.\n- **Agent information** — `agent.name`, `agent.id`, `agent.ip`. Tells\n  you which host produced the log entry.\n- **Original log data** — the raw event, parsed into structured fields\n  (e.g. `data.win.eventdata.commandLine`, `data.srcip`, `data.user`).\n\nWhen investigating, work top-down: read the rule description to get\nthe alert''s intent, check the agent to know where it happened, and\nfinally drill into the original log fields to understand the actual\nevent.\n\n## Common Alerts in This Environment\n\nThe following alert categories are frequently observed when running\nattacks against the lab:\n\n- **Authentication-related alerts.** Repeated failed logons, account\n  lockouts, and unusual account behavior. Look at\n  `data.win.eventdata.targetUserName` and `data.srcip` to identify the\n  affected account and origin.\n- **Process creation alerts.** Triggered by the execution of unusual\n  binaries or unusual command lines. Inspect\n  `data.win.eventdata.image` and `data.win.eventdata.commandLine`.\n- **PowerShell activity.** Suspicious or obfuscated PowerShell often\n  triggers high-level alerts. The encoded command, if present, is in\n  `data.win.eventdata.commandLine`.\n- **Registry modifications.** Persistence techniques typically modify\n  specific registry keys. Look at\n  `data.win.eventdata.targetObject`.\n- **Sysmon-driven detections.** Most of the high-fidelity Windows\n  alerts in this environment come from Sysmon events ingested by\n  Wazuh. They cover process creation, network connections, image\n  loads, and more.\n\n## A Simple Investigation Workflow\n\nWhen facing an alert you have not seen before, the following sequence\nkeeps things efficient:\n\n1. Read the rule description and check the rule level.\n2. Identify the agent: which lab host produced the alert?\n3. Open the full alert document and inspect the original log entry.\n4. Correlate with neighboring alerts on the same agent within a short\n   time window — most attacks produce several alerts in succession.\n5. Confirm or reject the hypothesis, then either escalate, tune the\n   rule (if the alert is a false positive), or move on.\n\n## Limitations\n\nThe default Wazuh ruleset is broad but not exhaustive. Some attacks\nperformed in the lab will not produce any alert at all, which is\nprecisely the gap that the platform''s purple-team cycle is designed to\nhelp detect and close.',
 'blue-team'),

-- 5. Writing detection rules (purple team / methodology)
('Writing, Testing and Deploying a Wazuh Detection Rule',
 'Step-by-step methodology for adding or improving a Wazuh detection rule, from gap identification to deployment and tuning.',
 '# Writing, Testing and Deploying a Wazuh Detection Rule\n\nThis guide describes the methodology for adding or improving a detection\nrule in Wazuh, in the context of the platform''s purple-team cycle. It is\nwritten as a step-by-step workflow that an analyst can follow when a\nsimulation has revealed a detection gap.\n\n## When to Write a New Rule\n\nA new rule is justified when one of the following situations occurs:\n\n- A simulated attack ran successfully but produced no Wazuh alert\n  (false negative).\n- An existing alert is too generic and lacks the context needed for\n  triage (low fidelity).\n- A new technique has been added to the offensive catalog and is not\n  covered by any existing rule.\n\nWriting a rule "just in case" — without a concrete case observed in the\nlab — should be avoided: it inflates the ruleset without improving\ncoverage.\n\n## Step 1 — Identify the Source Event\n\nEvery Wazuh rule reacts to a specific log entry. Before writing the\nrule, the corresponding log line must be identified.\n\n- Reproduce the attack in the lab.\n- Open the Wazuh Security Events module and search for any log entries\n  produced on the target host during the attack window. Even if no\n  alert was triggered, the underlying log may be present in the index.\n- Identify the precise event source (Windows Security log, Sysmon,\n  PowerShell operational log, etc.) and the field values that\n  characterize the malicious behavior.\n\nIf no log entry exists at all, the issue is not a missing rule but a\nmissing collection: the relevant event source must first be enabled on\nthe agent before any rule can be written.\n\n## Step 2 — Draft the Rule\n\nWazuh rules are written in XML and live under\n`/var/ossec/etc/rules/local_rules.xml` on the Wazuh manager. A rule is\nidentified by a numeric `id` (custom rules use IDs from `100000`\nupward) and a `level` from 0 to 15.\n\nA rule is composed of:\n\n- **Match conditions** — `field`, `match`, `regex` elements that filter\n  the incoming event.\n- **A description** — a short, human-readable sentence that will appear\n  on every alert produced by the rule.\n- **A level** — chosen according to the severity and reliability of the\n  detection.\n- **Optional MITRE ATT&CK tagging** — a reference to the technique ID\n  the rule covers, useful for reporting and tuning.\n\nThe rule should be as specific as possible. Overly broad conditions\ngenerate noise; overly narrow ones miss variants of the same technique.\n\n## Step 3 — Test the Rule\n\nWazuh ships with a command-line tool that lets analysts test a rule\nagainst sample log data without restarting the manager:\n\n`/var/ossec/bin/wazuh-logtest`\n\nThe tool reads a log line from stdin, runs it through the full rule\nengine, and prints which rule (if any) matches. Use it to verify that:\n\n- The rule matches the original malicious event.\n- The rule does **not** match a benign variant of the same event.\n- The level and description are produced as expected.\n\nThis step is essential. Skipping it almost always leads to either\nsilent failures or large bursts of false positives once the rule is\ndeployed.\n\n## Step 4 — Deploy the Rule\n\nOnce the rule has been validated, it is deployed by:\n\n1. Adding it to `local_rules.xml` on the Wazuh manager.\n2. Restarting the Wazuh manager service:\n   `systemctl restart wazuh-manager`.\n3. Reproducing the attack one more time and confirming that the alert\n   now appears in the dashboard with the expected level and\n   description.\n\n## Step 5 — Watch for False Positives\n\nA newly deployed rule must be observed for a short period before being\nconsidered stable. Two things are checked:\n\n- **Volume of alerts** — an unexpected spike usually indicates that the\n  rule is matching benign activity.\n- **Distribution across hosts** — alerts firing on every agent at once\n  are a strong false-positive signal.\n\nIf false positives appear, the rule should be tuned (made more\nspecific) rather than deleted. The lab provides a controlled\nenvironment in which several iterations of refinement can be performed\nquickly.\n\n## Step 6 — Document the Rule\n\nA short note describing the intent of the rule, the technique it\ncovers, and any known caveats should accompany every custom rule.\nWithout documentation, custom rules tend to accumulate and become\nunmaintainable, especially when several analysts contribute over time.',
 'purple-team'),

-- 6. MITRE ATT&CK techniques (placeholder)
('MITRE ATT&CK Techniques Available in Caldera',
 'Catalog of the offensive techniques available through Caldera, organized along the MITRE ATT&CK framework. To be completed.',
 '# MITRE ATT&CK Techniques Available in Caldera\n\n*This guide is reserved for future content. It will list and describe the\nattack techniques exposed through the Caldera offensive lab, organized\nalong the MITRE ATT&CK framework, with a short descriptor and an\nofficial MITRE link for each technique.*\n\n*Content to be added in a later iteration.*',
 'red-team');